1 a fee] enter into and comply with an agreement with the authority to reimburse the authority
2 for the costs of administering the program. [The fee] Any fee prescribed by the authority under
3 this subsection may not exceed 20 percent of the cost of the emergency medical services provided.
4 The authority shall allow up to 120 percent of the fee to be counted as an operating cost for pro-
5 viders.
6 (4) An emergency medical services provider shall make readily available to the authority doc-
7 umentation, data and certifications, as prescribed by the authority, necessary to establish that the
8 emergency medical services expenditures qualify for federal financial participation and to calculate
9 the amount due to a coordinated care organization for the expenditures.
10 (5) If the authority determines that any expenditure made by an emergency medical services
11 provider does not qualify for federal financial participation, the authority shall return the funds as-
12 sociated with the expenditure to the provider or [refuse to accept the transfer of funds associated with
13 the expenditure] exclude the expenditure before submitting a request for federal financial
14 participation.
15 (6) Participation by any coordinated care organization or emergency medical services provider
16 in the program must be voluntary.
17 (7) The authority shall consult with emergency medical services providers in the development,
18 implementation and operation of the [intergovernmental transfer program] funding mechanism de-
19 scribed in subsection (1) of this section.
20 SECTION 3. This 2026 Act being necessary for the immediate preservation of the public
21 peace, health and safety, an emergency is declared to exist, and this 2026 Act takes effect
22 on its passage.
